INTRODUCTION¶

This is a machine learning project which aims to find the best evaluation score for a given dataset.

The datasets have two files as training and test data where training data is used for modeling part while test data for evaluation part. These datasets are randomly selected from the original data.

Target variable vector consists of two classes called “a” and “b” whereas feature matrix includes both binary columns and continuous columns. Additionally, there is class imbalance, thus so minimization of error rate for each class should be considered. Area under ROC curve that is an indicator of performance for binary classification problems should be also maximized during model building. Additionally, balanced accuracy is another metric that we need to consider. The evaluation will be based on the average of these two metrics.

This project consist of 3 parts;

  • Data Engeering
  • Model Selection
  • Evaluation.

First, we focus on preprocessing of data including an investigation for outliers in each class, missing values, intensity of class imbalance, feature importance, and feature independence. In order to obtain results for our investigation we involve proximity matrix, boxplots,histograms related to proximity matrix results, heat maps, correlation matrix, and feature importance graphs.

Afterwards, we proceed to build some models that we deeply cover during courses. In that part we strive for using algorithms as much as possible due to the fact that algorithms may outweigh each other in terms of different concepts (for instance gradient boosting mainly focus on low biased structure whereas random forest focus on low variance structure). For regression models, we are so sensitive not to employ whole features to reduce variance or for algorithms which are close to support vector, gradient boosting and random forest concepts we strive for keeping whole feature information as much as possible to get strong learning, also we tune those model's parameters according to having nice accuracy and ROC values. Sometimes there are some cases we can not obtain results for relevant algorithm due to parameters that leads to high complexity, therefore faster training speed algorithms with sufficient efficiency such as light gbm, xgboost are also chosen over other algorithms.

APPROACH¶

Initially one of the biggest issue to what we must pay attention in our case is the class imbalance structure. Therefore we need to turn it into more balanced structure employing preprocessing methods. Imbalanced classification problem is kind of a classification problem where the distribution of instances for classes is biased, so it actually creates a challenge for models with respect to algorithms we learned in courses due to the fact that most of machine learning algorithms including classification were designed according to the assumption of an equal number of instances for each class. This leads to models that have poor predictive performance, especially for the minority class. This situation really poses a problem because the minority class can be ignored and the model has a great potential to make classification errors for the minority class than the majority class. In addition, we may have outliers in each class and if we do not cancel them out then our machine learning algoritms may give more deviated results because employing outliers we force our algorithms to try to predict them which is nonsense actually. According to potential issues we mentioned above, first we check each class whether or not outliers exist involving proximity matrix. Here we set our threshold 0.05, and we find that major class has some outliers whereas minor class has no outliers. Thus deleting outliers in major class results in both having more balanced structure in all data than it had before and having more homogeneity in major class itself.

Afterwards, using SMOTE-NC ( Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique with Nominal and Continuous Data ) we create synthetic instances for minor class to increase the balanced more in data. Here, employing nearest neighbour computation for minor class we take the convex computation for continuous features whereas for the binary features we take the majority of the k nearest neighbour. After we have reached balanced data in whole data, we again take a glance at outliers using proximity matrix and cancel them out.

Additionally, as an alternative to SMOTE-NC, we generated synthetic data by using proximity matrix.

After we reach balance structure and clean the outliers we do not apply any feature selection because first we aim to employ gradient boosting, random forest, support vector machine. Unlike the regression models, mentioned models are more robust, they do not have much more assumptions(such as error distribution assumption, independency assumption….) also in regression models having lots of features generally leads to low bias high variance or overfitness but in gbm, svm and random forest even we have lots of features we can tune the parameters easily and avoid the overfitness. In short without losing information by not deleting features, we have more easiness and potential to reach nice models for gbm, svm and random forest than regression models.

Random forest is an algorithm to reduce the variance because it consists of independent trees and taking the average or majority of results of each decision trees decrease the variance but this method is not aimed at reducing the bias specifically, so in order to have mainly decreased variance case we include random forest algorithm. In the gradient boosting algorithm, the main aim is to reduce the biasedness not the variance because for each iteration gradient boosting uses decision tree to estimate the residuals and this situation may give high variance for residuals, thus to have mainly decreased bias case we include gradient boosting algorithm. Regarding to support vector machine, we do not involve feature selection for linear and Gaussian kernel to keep the information as much as possible but for polynomial kernel we employ some selection techniques, because during the second degree and third degree polynomial for the 60 features we approximately have 3540 features combination which exceeds the number of instances and this circumstance disables the support vector algorithm to work effectively. With respect to feature selection, we apply PCA to continuous data keeping 99 percentage of information and employ feature importance graph which is calculated by dividing total impurity decrease over all trees in random forest with sum of the impurity decrease over all trees in random forest due to relevant feature. In short, we can reduce our 60 features to 15 features thus we can apply third and second degree polynomial kernel for support vector algorithm where approximately 225 features takes place.

We also want to include the distance based algorithm such as nearest neighbour although it may not give good results compared to other algorithms because of the fact that scaling issues and curse of dimensionality negatively affect our case. For instance, during the calculation of distances just one feature whose absolute values are so much higher than other features may take place or minimum distance and maximum distance gap for a relevant instance may so close due to curse of dimensionality. We know standardisation of features can alleviate scaling issues but we also disrupt the information among the features and can not even know how much information we lose unlike PCA method. So, we do not devote our time and energy to distance based methods and we are so careful for the calculation of how much information or total feature importance is lost if we are forced to reduce the features to employ relevant algorithms. Additionally, we involve logistic regression using less features according to feature importance graph in order to decrease variance in model whereas keeping information carried by features as much as possible. However, logistic regression model can not yield results as good as boosting,random forest and support vector models can yield.

It must be confessed that algorithms mentioned above are capable of consuming time,energy and memory tremendously for instance support vector algorithm with high penalized constant and low gamma value or gradient boosting with high number trees with low learning rate, so we take light gbm method into account which is working according to leaf based structure instead of level based in decision trees. Thus we can achieve faster training speed and high efficiency, lower memory usage, accuracy as good as gradient boosting at least. In addition to that, xgboost algorithm is capable of having more information about the direction of gradient because of the fact that at each step it is calculating second order gradients to minimise the loss function thus we can train faster and deliver higher performance than gradient boosting algorithm.

Data Engineering¶

In this part our main appproach was to create as many different datasets as possible in order to increase the performance. Thus we applied different feature selection techniques, outlier detection methods, scaling techniques and sampling methods.

Our data engineering part consists of two main approaches; Distribution based, Model Based data engineering.

Instance Selection¶

Distribution Based¶
In [55]:
def remove_outlier(df,n=3,m=30):
    cont = [i for i in df.columns if i not in category_features(df,threshold1=m)]
    df1=df[cont].copy()
    df1_mean, df1_std = df1.mean(), df1.std()
    cut_off = df1_std * n
    lower, upper = df1_mean - cut_off, df1_mean + cut_off
    df2=df1[(df1>lower) & (df1<upper)]
    ind=pd.isnull(df2).any(1).nonzero()[0]
    df3=df.index.isin(ind)
    df4=df[~df3].copy()
    return df4.reset_index(drop=True)
Model Based¶
In [27]:
def proximityMatrix(model, X, normalize=True):      

    terminals = model.apply(X)
    nTrees = terminals.shape[1]

    a = terminals[:,0]
    proxMat = 1*np.equal.outer(a, a)

    for i in range(1, nTrees):
        a = terminals[:,i]
        proxMat += 1*np.equal.outer(a, a)

    if normalize:
        proxMat = proxMat / nTrees

    return proxMat

def proximity_calculation(data):
    ###Before proximity matrix, create syntetic data
    col=len(data.columns)-1
    matrix = np.transpose(np.array(data))
    np.random.permutation(matrix[col])
    permutated = pd.DataFrame()
    for i in range (0,col):
        perm = np.random.permutation(matrix[i])
        permutated[i] = perm

    permutated.columns = data.iloc[:,0:col].columns
    permutated['class'] = np.full(len(data),0)

    ##create copy for original data
    data_copy = data.iloc[:,0:col]
    data_copy['class'] = np.full(len(data),1)

    #concat syntetic and original instances
    data_combined = pd.concat([data_copy,permutated],ignore_index= True)
    
    inputs = data_combined.iloc[:,0:col]
    target = data_combined.iloc[:,col]
    model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=500, max_features=2, min_samples_leaf=40)
    model.fit(inputs, target)
    prox_matrix = proximityMatrix(model, inputs, normalize=True)
    return prox_matrix,permutated,data_copy,data_combined

def proximity_removed_df(df,threshold=0.05,dist_measure=10,hist=False):

    y=df.iloc[:,-1]
    x=df.drop(columns=[y.name])
    
    major=df[df['y']==0]

    major_prox, major_perm, major_copy,major_combined = proximity_calculation(data = major)
    ###Just for original data proximity matrix
    major_prox_df = pd.DataFrame(major_prox[0:major.shape[0],0:major.shape[0]])
    
    ##counting the points that proximity value is less than 0.10
    count = []
    for i in range(0,major.shape[0]):
        count.append(sum(major_prox_df[i] < threshold))
    
    ##less than 5 are taken
    major_new = major[np.array(count) < dist_measure]
    
    minor=df[df['y']==1]
    new_df=pd.concat([major_new,minor],axis=0)
    new_df.reset_index(inplace=True,drop=True)
    return new_df

In [17]:
def selected_features(df):
    y=df.iloc[:,-1]
    x=df.drop(columns=[y.name])
    sel = SelectFromModel(RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = 100))
    sel.fit(x, y)
    selected_feat= x.columns[(sel.get_support())]
    return selected_feat

def model_based_df(df,selected_feat):
    y=df.iloc[:,-1]
    x=df[selected_feat]
    return pd.concat([x,y],axis=1)

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

def scaling(df,test):
    scaler=StandardScaler()
    if test:
        x=df
        return pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(x))
    else:
        y=df.iloc[:,-1]
        x=df.drop(columns=[y.name])
        transformed_x=pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(x))
        return pd.concat([transformed_x,y],axis=1)

After several trials, we found that standardscaler yielded better result compare to other scaling methods.

Sampling and Data Generation¶

In [28]:
def proximity_generated_df(df,border=0.4,hist=False):

    y=df.iloc[:,-1]
    x=df.drop(columns=[y.name])
    
    minor=df[df['y']==1]

    minor_prox, minor_perm, minor_copy,minor_combined = proximity_calculation(data = minor)
    ###Just for original data proximity matrix
    minor_prox_df = pd.DataFrame(minor_prox[0:minor.shape[0],0:minor.shape[0]])

    ###Compare syntetic data and original data
    syntetic_proc = pd.DataFrame(minor_prox[minor.shape[0]:,minor.shape[0]:])
    ##average proximity value
    mean = []
    for i in range(0,minor.shape[0]):
        mean.append(np.mean(syntetic_proc.iloc[i]))
    if hist:
        pd.DataFrame(mean).hist()

    index = np.array(mean) > border
    syntetic = minor_combined.iloc[minor.shape[0]:,0:minor.shape[1]-1]
    syntetic.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    syntetic = syntetic[index]
    syntetic.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    syntetic['y'] = np.full(len(syntetic),1)
    
    
    final_df = pd.concat([df,syntetic])
    final_df.reset_index(inplace=True,drop=True)
    return final_df
In [21]:
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTENC 

def SMOTENC_sample(df,strategy):
    y=df.iloc[:,-1]
    x=df.drop(columns=[y.name])
    cat_names=category_features(x,20)
    cat_features = [x.columns.get_loc(c) for c in cat_names]
    smote=SMOTENC(sampling_strategy=strategy, categorical_features=cat_features)
    X,Y= smote.fit_resample(x, y)
    return pd.concat([X,Y],axis=1)

from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures

def poly_transform(df,test=False):
    poly=PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)
    
    if test:
        x=df
        x_transformed=pd.DataFrame(poly.fit_transform(x))
    else:
        y=df.iloc[:,-1]
        x=df.drop(columns=[y.name])
        poly_x=pd.DataFrame(poly.fit_transform(x))
        x_transformed=pd.concat([poly_x,y],axis=1)
    return x_transformed

Main¶

In [29]:
def main(df,df_test,remove_outliers,proximity_outlier,standard_scale,polynomial_transform,model_based_selection,generate_instance,smote,strategy=0.5,border=0.45):
    if remove_outliers:
        df=remove_outlier(df)
    
    if proximity_outlier:
        df=proximity_removed_df(df,threshold=0.05,dist_measure=5)
        
    if standard_scale:
        df=scaling(df,test=False)
        df_test=scaling(df_test,test=True)
    
    if polynomial_transform:
        df=poly_transform(df,test=False)
        df_test=poly_transform(df_test,test=True)
     
    if model_based_selection:
        sel_feats=selected_features(df)
        df=model_based_df(df,sel_feats)
        df_test=df_test[sel_feats]
   
    if generate_instance:
        df=proximity_generated_df(df,border=border)
   
    
    if smote:
        df=SMOTENC_sample(df,strategy)
        
        
    return df,df_test

Model Selection¶

For model selection, we used RandomizedCV method. RandomizedCV is library in sklearn which enables performing k-folds cross validation for given parameters. In this section we defined search spaces for each model. Furthermore, we defined a custom metric which would give us the intended score.

def lgbm_final_model(df,iter_size,cv):
    
    y=df.iloc[:,-1]
    x=df.drop(columns=[y.name])
    
    param_test ={'boosting_type':['gbdt'],
                 'n_estimators':sp_randint(30, 300),
                 'objective':['binary'],
                 'learning_rate':list(np.logspace(np.log10(0.01), np.log10(0.2), base = 10, num = 100)),
                 'num_leaves': sp_randint(6, 50), 
                 'min_child_samples': sp_randint(50, 500), 
                 'min_child_weight': [1e-5, 1e-3, 1e-2, 1e-1, 1, 1e1, 1e2, 1e3, 1e4],
                 'subsample': sp_uniform(loc=0.2, scale=0.8), 
                 'colsample_bytree': sp_uniform(loc=0.4, scale=0.6),
                 'reg_alpha': [0, 1e-1, 1, 2, 5, 7, 10, 50, 100],
                 'reg_lambda': [0, 1e-1, 1, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100]}
    
    n_HP_points_to_test = iter_size
    
    clf = lgb.LGBMClassifier(max_depth=-1, random_state=SEED, silent=True, metric='auc', n_jobs=3)
    
    gs = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=clf, param_distributions=param_test, 
                            n_iter=n_HP_points_to_test,
                            scoring = {'AUC': 'roc_auc',
                                       'BAL': make_scorer(balanced_accuracy_score,greater_is_better=True),
                                       'ROC': make_scorer(roc_auc_score,greater_is_better=True)},
                            cv=cv,
                            refit='AUC',
                            random_state=SEED,
                            verbose=True,
                            n_jobs=-1)
    
    
    gs.fit(x, y)
    
    results=gs.cv_results_    
    
    
    results['AVR']= (results['mean_test_ROC'] + results['mean_test_BAL'])/2
    
    
    i1 = results['AVR'].argmax()
    
    opt_parameters1=results['params'][i1]
    
    opt_score=results['AVR'][i1]
    
    clf_final = lgb.LGBMClassifier(**clf.get_params())
    
    clf_final.set_params(**opt_parameters1)
    
    return clf_final,opt_score

def xgbm_final_model(df,iter_size,cv):
    
    y=df.iloc[:,-1]
    x=df.drop(columns=[y.name])
    
    param_test ={'boosting_type':['gbtree'], 
                 'n_estimators':sp_randint(30, 300),
                 'objective':['binary:logistic'],                 
                 'max_depth': sp_randint(3, 50),
                 'gamma':[0, 1e-2,1e-1, 1, 2, 5, 7, 10, 50, 100],
                 'learning_rate':list(np.logspace(np.log10(0.01), np.log10(0.2), base = 10, num = 100)),
                 'num_leaves': sp_randint(6, 50), 
                 'min_child_samples': sp_randint(50, 500), 
                 'min_child_weight': [1e-5, 1e-3, 1e-2, 1e-1, 1, 1e1, 1e2, 1e3, 1e4],
                 'subsample': sp_uniform(loc=0.2, scale=0.8), 
                 'colsample_bytree': sp_uniform(loc=0.4, scale=0.6),
                 'reg_alpha': [0, 1e-1, 1, 2, 5, 7, 10, 50, 100],
                 'reg_lambda': [0, 1e-1, 1, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100]}
    
    n_HP_points_to_test = iter_size
    
    clf = xgb.XGBClassifier(random_state=SEED, silent=True, metric='auc', n_jobs=3)
    
    gs = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=clf, param_distributions=param_test, 
                            n_iter=n_HP_points_to_test,
                            scoring = {'AUC': 'roc_auc',
                                       'BAL': make_scorer(balanced_accuracy_score,greater_is_better=True),
                                       'ROC': make_scorer(roc_auc_score,greater_is_better=True)},
                            cv=cv,
                            refit='AUC',
                            random_state=SEED,
                            verbose=True,
                            n_jobs=-1)

    gs.fit(x, y)
    
    results=gs.cv_results_    
    
    
    results['AVR']= (results['mean_test_ROC'] + results['mean_test_BAL'])/2
    
    
    i1 = results['AVR'].argmax()
    
    opt_parameters1=results['params'][i1]
    
    opt_score=results['AVR'][i1]
    
    clf_final = xgb.XGBClassifier(**clf.get_params())
    
    clf_final.set_params(**opt_parameters1)
    
    return clf_final,opt_score

def get_results_df(results):
    dfs=[]
    models=[]
    scores=[]

    for k,v in results.items():
        mdl=v[0]
        for i in mdl:
            name = str(i).split('(')[0]
            models.append(name)
        scr=v[1]
        for i in scr:
            scores.append(i)
            dfs.append(k)

    df=pd.DataFrame({
                     'df': dfs,
                     'model': models,
                     'score': scores
                    })
    return df

results_df=get_results_df(results)

CONCLUSION and FUTURE WORK¶

We created multiple dataset which differentiate from each other by their methods of data engineering. Then we applied multiple learning approaches to these datasets. In order to obtain the best performing model, we optimized our learning parameters by tunning it with a custom metric in randomized search with cross validation. This process gave us the average score, which is calculated by the average of ROC AUC and balanced accuracy, for each model belong to each dataset. The graph above shows the scores of different approaches.

In the graph, df_0 is the raw data without any manuplation thus it gives the worst scores. It is acts like benchmark for measuring improvement in scores. df_2 is the case where we applied standard scaling, model based instance selection, and SMOTE-NC respectively. df_3 is the case where we applied distribution based instance selection, standart scaling and SMOTE-NC respectively. df_2 and df_3 seem the optimal dataset candidates for the learning problem. Also, there is no remarkable difference between df_2 and df_3 in terms of performance but both perform much better than df_1.

Moreover, if we examine the performance of each model, we observed that, xgboost gave the best result compare to other models in all datasets. Another gradient boosting method, lgbm is the second best performing candidate among the models. These two models perform significantly better than the other models.

The optimal parameter set of xgboost is below;

  • 'objective': 'binary:logistic',
  • 'use_label_encoder': True,
  • 'colsample_bytree': 0.7801178264565368,
  • 'gamma': 0,
  • 'importance_type': 'gain',
  • 'learning_rate': 0.08834940584779542,
  • 'max_depth': 8,
  • 'min_child_weight': 0.01,
  • 'missing': nan,
  • 'n_estimators': 177,
  • 'reg_alpha': 1,
  • 'reg_lambda': 0.1,
  • 'subsample': 0.6096744466394248,
  • 'boosting_type': 'gbtree',
  • 'min_child_samples': 398,
  • 'num_leaves': 41

Undoubtedly, there are many methods and algorithms to enhance the accuracy and ROC value further. For instance: After feature selection via feature importance graph, group lasso can be employed where we can create groups using binary features combination regarding to design matrix and can assign continuous features to them and we can examine each group separately for continuous features just solving minimised squared error with relevant constraints, or ANCOVA logistic regression can be employed where we can create design matrix having different coefficients for different groups with respect to continuous data and can optimize log likelihood structure including logit function thus can examine each group separately, or model based regression trees can be employed where splits are chosen with just selected binary features and for the terminal nodes we apply regression models. In addition, without any feature selection at the beginning, stepwise regression models can be employed where we can eliminate features or eliminate grouping effect according to significance levels of parameters (such as p-values…) or maximum log likelihood ratio test.

def object_features(df):
    return list(df.loc[:,df.dtypes=='object'].columns)

def numeric_features(df):
    return list(df.loc[:,(df.dtypes=='int64')|(df.dtypes=='float64')].columns)


def category_features(df,threshold1,threshold2=0):    
    category_features = []
    for each in df.columns:
        if threshold2 < df[each].nunique() < threshold1:
            category_features.append(each)
    return category_features

def check_type(y):
    try:
        condition=y.nunique()
    except:
        condition=len(np.unique(y))
    if condition==1:
        return 'No Label' 
    elif condition==2:
        return 'Classification' 
    elif 2<condition<10:
        return 'Multi-Class Classification'
    else:
        return 'Regression'

def check_imbalance(y):
    if check_type(y)!='Regression':
        return pd.concat([y.value_counts(),y.value_counts(normalize=True)],axis=1)
    
def check_missing_value(df):
    return any(df.isna().sum()!=0)

def get_y(df):
    return df.iloc[:,-1]

def get_x(df):
    return df.iloc[:,:-1]

def information_table(df):    
    number_instance = df.shape[0]
    number_feature  = df.shape[1]
    
    y=df.iloc[:,-1]
    x=df.iloc[:,:-1]
    
    instance = x.shape[0]
    
    y_type = check_type(y)
        
    number_numeric  = len(numeric_features(x))
    number_object   = len(object_features(x))
    
    missing_value = check_missing_value(x)
    
    imbalance = check_imbalance(y)
    
    same_value = category_features(x,2)
    
    binary = category_features(x,3,1)
    
    category = category_features(x,30,3)
    
    continous = [i for i in x.columns if i not in category_features(x,30)]
    
    print('Dataset has ' + str(number_instance) + ' instances and ' + str(number_feature) + ' features.')
    print('Data has ' + str(instance) + ' instances.')
    print('Class Type is ' + y_type +'.')
    print('Data has ' + str(number_numeric) + ' numeric and ' + str(number_object) + ' object features.')
    print('Features: ' + str(same_value) + ' have same values.')
    print('Features: ' + str(binary) + ' are binary.')
    print('Binary Features number: ' + str(len(binary)))
    
    print('Features:' +str(category_features(x,30,3)) + ' might be categorical. (Unique values are less than 30)')
    
    print('Features:' +str(continous) + ' might be continous.')
    if missing_value:
        print('Data has missing value.')
    else:
        print('Data has no missing value.')
    if y_type != 'Regression':
        print('Lets examine imbalance:')
        print(imbalance)
    else:
        plt.hist(y)
        plt.title('Histogram ' + y.name)
    
    return binary,same_value,category,continous

def skewed_features(df,threshold,n=30):
    cont = [i for i in df.columns if i not in category_features(df,threshold1=n)]
    skew=df[cont].skew().abs()
    return skew[skew>threshold]

def correlated_pairs(df,threshold):
    corr=df.corr()
    indices = np.where(corr > threshold)
    indices = [(corr.index[x], corr.columns[y]) for x, y in zip(*indices) if x != y and x < y]
    return indices



def drop_correlated(df,threshold):
    corr_matrix = df.corr().abs()
    upper = corr_matrix.where(np.triu(np.ones(corr_matrix.shape), k=1).astype(np.bool))

    to_drop = [column for column in upper.columns if any(upper[column] > threshold)]
    print(to_drop)
    return df.drop(to_drop, axis=1)

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler,MinMaxScaler,RobustScaler,QuantileTransformer,Normalizer




def merge_dicts(*dict_args):
    result = {}
    for dictionary in dict_args:
        result.update(dictionary)
    return result

def get_cont(df,n=30):
    cont = [i for i in df.columns if i not in category_features(df,threshold1=n)]
    return df[cont]
    
def get_n_cont(df,n=30):
    n_cont = [i for i in df.columns if i  in category_features(df,threshold1=n)]
    return df[n_cont]

def combine(df1,df2):
    return pd.concat([df1,df2], axis=1)
    

def multiple_scale(df,scalers,outlier=False):
    if outlier:
        return {k+'_outlier':combine(pd.DataFrame(v.fit_transform(get_cont(df))),get_n_cont(df)) for k,v in scalers.items()}
    else:
        return {k:combine(pd.DataFrame(v.fit_transform(get_cont(df))),get_n_cont(df)) for k,v in scalers.items()}

def apply_multiple_scale(df,scalers,test=False):
    df1=drop_correlated(df,0.92) #manuel test
    scaled_dfs1=multiple_scale(df1,scalers) #teste uygula
    
    df1=drop_correlated(df,0.92) #manuel test
    if test:
        df2=df1
    else:
        df2=remove_outlier(df1)
    scaled_dfs2=multiple_scale(df2,scalers,True) #teste uygula
    
    scaled_dfs=merge_dicts(scaled_dfs1,scaled_dfs2)
    return scaled_dfs

from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures


def perform_poly(scaled_train,scaled_test):
    poly=PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)
    transformed_train={}
    for k,v in scaled_train.items():
        x=get_x(v)
        poly_x=pd.DataFrame(poly.fit_transform(x))
        x_transformed=pd.concat([poly_x,get_y(v)],axis=1)
        transformed_train.update({k:v})
        transformed_train.update({str(k)+'_poly':x_transformed})
    transformed_test={}
    for k,v in scaled_test.items():
        test=v
        poly_test=poly.fit_transform(test)
        test_transformed=pd.DataFrame(poly_test)
        transformed_test.update({k:v})
        transformed_test.update({str(k)+'_poly':test_transformed})
    return transformed_train,transformed_test

def train_test(df,size=0.25,random_state=SEED):
    y=df.iloc[:,-1]
    x=df.drop(columns=[y.name])
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=size, random_state=random_state, stratify=y)
    return x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test
